{"key":"processedPost-11018049","value":{"id":11018049,"first":5831095,"last":11196420,"when":1252388590,"utime":"09/08/09 08:43 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />i think this is quit clear as to the need to isolate then clone instead of just cloning.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />When you isolate, you don't need to clone because you save well-labeled mycelium from each culture under refrigeration.&nbsp; Later, when you determine the best isolates, you go back to your culture collection and grab that specific one to grow out.&nbsp; This way, you always have very young cell lines, not months old cell lines from a clone.&nbsp; <br /><br />These juvenile cell lines stored in master slants are how commercial mushroom farms stay in business.&nbsp; If they kept cloning, all their cultures would fade out due to senescence.<br />RR","title":"Re: differences between strain isolation by transfers and by cloning?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}